This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it introduces a novel CNN-based feature point detector for image matching and registration. The paper also mentions the application of the method on retinal images, which falls under the medical image analysis sub-field of computer vision. 

The paper also involves machine learning techniques, specifically semi-supervised learning, which suggests that it could also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. 

Additionally, the paper involves optimization techniques for maximizing correct matching, which could also place it in the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. 

The use of CNNs for feature point detection suggests that it could also belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category. 

Finally, the paper involves image retrieval and matching, which could also place it in the information retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category.
